ivate, and Spirit Worlds -- tSex and Sexuality: The Public, the Private, and the Spirit Worlds -- tSpace in the Early American City -- tA History of all Religions -- tQuestions, Suspicions, Speculations -- tAfterword: The Quest for Universal Understanding -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPenned by leading historians, the specially-commissioned essays of Whither the Early Republic represent the most stimulating and innovative work being done on imperialism, environmental history, slavery, economic history, politics, and culture in the early Republic.The past fifteen years have seen a dramatic expansion in the scope of scholarship on the history of the early American republic. Whither the Early Republic consists of innovative essays on all aspects of the culture and society of this period, including Indians and empire, the economy and the environment, slavery and culture, and gender and urban life. Penned by leading historians, the essays are arranged thematically to reflect areas of change and growth in the field.Throughout the book, preeminent scholars act as guides for students to their areas of expertise. Contributors include Pulitzer Prize-winner Alan Taylor, Bancroft Prize-winner James Brooks, Christopher Clark, Ted Steinberg, Walter Johnson, Patricia Cline Cohen, David Waldstreicher, and more. These essays, all originally commissioned to appear in a special issue of the Journal of the Early Republic, explore a diverse array of subjects: the struggles for control of North America; the economic culture of the early Republic; the interactions of humans with plants, climate, animals, and germs; the commodification of people; and the complex intersections of politics and culture.Whither the Early Republic offers a wealth of tools for introducing a new generation of historians to the nature of the field and also to the wide array of possibilities that lie in the future for scholars of this fascinating period.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 4aAmerican Studies. 7aHISTORY / United States / Revolutionary Period (1775-1800).2bisacsh  aAmerican History.  aAmerican Studies.1 aBolton Valenčius, Conevery, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrooks, James F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClark, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCline Cohen, Patricia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavenport, Stewart, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDonahue, Brian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFenn, Elizabeth A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHerman, Bernard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHuston, James L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnson, Walter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLarson, John Lauritz, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLauritz Larson, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorrison, Michael A ., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorrison, Michael A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aReséndez, Andrés, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchmidt, Leigh E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShields, David S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmallwood, Stephanie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStanley, Amy Dru, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/re